  "prompt": "I'm a US citizen and my boyfriend is Argentinean; if we get married in the US, how long will it take for him to be qualified to work in the US?",
  "response": "Congratulations on your upcoming marriage! Navigating the U.S. immigration process can be complex, but I can provide a general overview of how your Argentinean boyfriend can obtain the authorization to work in the United States after marrying you. Here's a step-by-step guide along with estimated timelines:\n\n### 1. **Marriage in the U.S.**\nEnsure that your marriage is legally recognized in the state where it takes place. Proper documentation will be essential for the subsequent immigration process.\n\n### 2. **Apply for a Green Card (Permanent Residency)**\nAs a U.S. citizen marrying a foreign national, your spouse can apply for a marriage-based green card. This process involves several steps:\n\n#### **a. File Form I-130 (Petition for Alien Relative)**\n- **Purpose:** Establishes the relationship between you and your spouse.\n- **Timeline:** Typically takes 5-12 months for processing, depending on the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) workload.\n\n#### **b. File Form I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status)**\n- **Purpose:** If your spouse is already in the U.S., this form adjusts their status to a permanent resident.\n- **Concurrent Filing:** You can file Form I-130 and Form I-485 simultaneously, which can expedite the process.\n- **Timeline:** Generally takes 8-14 months from submission to approval.\n\n### 3. **Obtain Work Authorization (Employment Authorization Document - EAD)**\nWhile the green card application is being processed, your spouse can apply for work authorization.\n\n#### **a. File Form I-765 (Application for Employment Authorization)**\n- **Purpose:** Allows your spouse to legally work in the U.S. while waiting for the green card.\n- **Tie to I-485:** This is typically filed concurrently with Form I-485.\n- **Timeline:** Once filed, it usually takes about 3-5 months to receive the EAD.\n\n### 4. **Additional Steps and Considerations**\n- **Biometrics Appointment:** Your spouse will need to attend a biometrics appointment where fingerprints and photographs are taken.\n- **Interview:** USCIS may schedule an interview for both of you to verify the authenticity of your marriage.\n- **Green Card Approval:** After all steps are successfully completed, your spouse will receive their green card, granting permanent residency and the right to work in the U.S.\n\n### 5. **Overall Estimated Timeline**\n- **Total Time from Marriage to Work Authorization:** Approximately 10-18 months.\n  - **EAD Availability:** Your spouse can begin working as soon as they receive the EAD, typically 3-5 months after applying.\n  - **Green Card:** Final approval may take an additional 8-14 months.\n\n### 6. **Alternative: K-1 Fianc\u00e9 Visa**\nIf you are not yet married, another pathway is the K-1 fianc\u00e9 visa:\n- **Purpose:** Allows your fianc\u00e9(e) to enter the U.S. for 90 days to get married.\n- **Process:** After marriage, your spouse can then apply for adjustment of status (Form I-485) and work authorization (Form I-765).\n- **Timeline:** The K-1 visa process typically takes about 6-9 months, followed by the adjustment of status process.\n\n### 7. **Important Tips**\n- **Maintain Legal Status:** Ensure that your spouse maintains a valid visa or legal status while in the U.S. to avoid complications.\n- **Prepare Documentation:** Gather all necessary documents, such as proof of relationship, financial support, and identity verification, to support the applications.\n- **Seek Professional Advice:** Consider consulting with an immigration attorney to navigate complexities and ensure all forms are correctly completed.\n\n### 8. **Working During the Process**\nOnce your spouse files Form I-765, they can legally work in the U.S. while awaiting the EAD approval. It's advisable to apply for the EAD as early as possible to minimize the waiting period.\n\n### Summary\nAfter marrying in the U.S., your Argentinean spouse can typically obtain work authorization within **3-5 months** by filing for an Employment Authorization Document (EAD) alongside the green card application. The entire process to obtain permanent residency might take **10-18 months**, depending on various factors like USCIS processing times and the completeness of your application.\n\n**Note:** Immigration laws and processing times can change, so it's essential to check the [USCIS website](https://www.uscis.gov/) for the most current information or consult with an immigration attorney.",
